THE NYC BRANCH

22
00:01:13,532 --> 00:01:14,992
WAS A HUGE HIT

23
00:01:15,075 --> 00:01:16,159
YUM

24
00:01:16,243 --> 00:01:19,871
ON THE NEW YORK TIMES'
TOP 8 NEW YORK CITY DISHES LIST

25
00:01:19,955 --> 00:01:22,499
LA POP-UP STORE, TOKYO BRANCH,
PARIS POP-UP STORE

26
00:01:22,583 --> 00:01:24,418
THE WORLD IS CAPTIVATED

27
00:01:24,501 --> 00:01:26,837
BY THE KOREAN <i>DWEJI-GOMTANG</i>

28
00:01:27,546 --> 00:01:29,673
HE IS INSPIRING THE WORLD

29
00:01:29,756 --> 00:01:33,260
KOREAN CUISINE CHEF OK DONG-SIK

30
00:01:34,678 --> 00:01:37,264
This is a space where people
are read like books, Hodong's Bookshop,

31
00:01:37,347 --> 00:01:40,225
located in the cutest neighborhood
in the world,

32
00:01:40,309 --> 00:01:41,810
Kangho-dong.

33
00:01:41,893 --> 00:01:43,437
- Welcome.
- Thank you.

34
00:01:43,979 --> 00:01:45,022
Nice to meet you.

35
00:01:45,981 --> 00:01:47,858
- Are you here to sell a book?
- Yes.

36
00:01:47,941 --> 00:01:50,902
We don't accept cash or credit cards here.

37
00:01:51,403 --> 00:01:52,696
We only accept "stories."

38
00:01:52,779 --> 00:01:54,740
- In English since you came from New York.
- All right.

39
00:01:54,823 --> 00:01:57,492
I'll set a price after hearing your story.

40
00:01:57,576 --> 00:01:58,994
- I understand.
- Okay.

41
00:01:59,077 --> 00:02:00,370
I hope you'll set a good price for it.

42
00:02:02,664 --> 00:02:04,666
I don't know if it's just me,

43
00:02:04,750 --> 00:02:07,169
SUDDENLY SENSING HIS GAZE
because I'm insecure,

44
00:02:07,252 --> 00:02:08,545
- but I feel like
- Yes?

45
00:02:08,629 --> 00:02:10,255
- you're looking at me
- Okay.

46
00:02:10,422 --> 00:02:12,591
and grading me like pork.

47
00:02:14,635 --> 00:02:16,970
- Not at all.
- You're not?

48
00:02:17,054 --> 00:02:18,805
- Not staring at my neck?
- Not at all.

49
00:02:18,889 --> 00:02:19,973
At everything.

50
00:02:20,849 --> 00:02:22,517
KEEP ASKING TO GET THE ANSWER YOU WANT

51
00:02:22,601 --> 00:02:23,518
- I see.
- Yes.

52
00:02:23,602 --> 00:02:25,270
I do have a nice neck.

53
00:02:25,354 --> 00:02:26,897
You have nice shoulders.

54
00:02:26,980 --> 00:02:28,899
- This cut?
- Yes.

55
00:02:29,816 --> 00:02:31,568
I usually use that cut.

56
00:02:31,652 --> 00:02:32,903
- This part?
- Yes.

57
00:02:32,986 --> 00:02:35,072
Which part is that exactly?
Can you show me?

58
00:02:35,155 --> 00:02:36,823
Mostly this part.

59
00:02:36,907 --> 00:02:38,116
I shouldn't do that.

60
00:02:39,534 --> 00:02:40,494
I knew it.

61
00:02:40,577 --> 00:02:42,245
He was grading me with his eyes.

62
00:02:43,163 --> 00:02:44,122
Right?

63
00:02:44,206 --> 00:02:45,165
I wasn't.

64
00:02:46,750 --> 00:02:48,168
All right.

65
00:02:48,251 --> 00:02:49,878
- In the reservation process,
- Yes?

66
00:02:49,961 --> 00:02:51,922
- you filled in this card. Here.
- I did.

67
00:02:52,005 --> 00:02:53,548
First, what's your name?

68
00:02:54,049 --> 00:02:55,801
My name is Ok Dong-sik.

69
00:02:55,884 --> 00:02:57,219
- I can confirm that.
- All right.

70
00:02:57,302 --> 00:02:58,428
And your restaurant?

71
00:02:58,512 --> 00:03:00,555
It's also called Okdongsik.

72
00:03:01,640 --> 00:03:04,059
- Your name?
- Ok Dong-sik.

73
00:03:04,309 --> 00:03:06,853
- And the restaurant?
- Okdongsik.

74
00:03:08,063 --> 00:03:09,564
Then I'll be promoting your restaurant

75
00:03:09,648 --> 00:03:12,150
every time I call your name.

76
00:03:12,359 --> 00:03:13,402
It is what it is.

77
00:03:15,195 --> 00:03:17,989
THIS SHOW IS CALLED <i>HODONG'S BOOKSHOP</i>

78
00:03:18,073 --> 00:03:19,700
Do they have the same meaning?

79
00:03:19,783 --> 00:03:20,992
No, they don't.

80
00:03:21,076 --> 00:03:24,496
My name is <i>"Ok" </i>as in "marble,"
<i>"dong"</i> as in "east," <i>"sik"</i> as in "plant."

81
00:03:24,579 --> 00:03:26,289
"A tree to be planted in the east."

82
00:03:26,373 --> 00:03:28,875
- A tree...
- To be planted in the east.

83
00:03:28,959 --> 00:03:32,170
Maybe that's why I went to New York,

84
00:03:32,254 --> 00:03:33,505
since it's east of South Korea.

85
00:03:34,506 --> 00:03:36,800
- Just like your name.
- Yes, like my name.

86
00:03:36,883 --> 00:03:38,844
- A tree to be planted in the east.
- Yes.

87
00:03:38,927 --> 00:03:39,886
And your restaurant?

88
00:03:39,970 --> 00:03:41,388
The restaurant Okdongsik

89
00:03:41,471 --> 00:03:42,431
is <i>"Ok"</i> as in "house,"

90
00:03:42,514 --> 00:03:44,516
<i>"dong"</i> as in "one kind,"
and <i>"sik"</i> as in "eat."

91
00:03:44,599 --> 00:03:46,226
"A house where you eat one kind of food."

92
00:03:46,309 --> 00:03:48,061
So, a restaurant serving one dish.

93
00:03:48,145 --> 00:03:50,981
- Because you have one item on the menu.
- That's right.

94
00:03:51,440 --> 00:03:52,941
I know you have branches

95
00:03:53,024 --> 00:03:54,693
- in different countries.
- Yes.

96
00:03:54,776 --> 00:03:56,445
How do foreigners pronounce it?

97
00:03:56,528 --> 00:03:57,446
Okdongsik?

98
00:03:58,905 --> 00:04:01,074
Yes, I suppose.

99
00:04:01,158 --> 00:04:03,118
What did you put under "occupation"?

100
00:04:03,535 --> 00:04:05,454
I put "chef."

101
00:04:05,912 --> 00:04:07,205
I did some research

102
00:04:07,289 --> 00:04:08,749
- since you made a reservation.
- Okay.

103
00:04:08,832 --> 00:04:11,001
Actually, as much as you're a chef,

104
00:04:11,084 --> 00:04:14,087
you're also a businessman now.

105
00:04:14,171 --> 00:04:15,505
You're more of the latter.

106
00:04:15,589 --> 00:04:18,967
But being a chef is still deep in my DNA.

107
00:04:19,050 --> 00:04:20,761
But I already know

108
00:04:20,844 --> 00:04:23,305
that you have branches
in New York and other places.

109
00:04:23,388 --> 00:04:25,974
- You're expanding worldwide.
- I am.

110
00:04:26,057 --> 00:04:28,852
- So, you're here to sell a book.
- Yes.

111
00:04:28,935 --> 00:04:30,604
What book did you bring?

112
00:04:30,729 --> 00:04:31,897
Today, I brought this.

113
00:04:32,606 --> 00:04:35,400
<i>How to Win Friends and Influence People</i>.

114
00:04:35,484 --> 00:04:36,610
- I see.
- Yes.

115
00:04:36,693 --> 00:04:37,944
HODONG'S BOOKSHOP

116
00:04:38,487 --> 00:04:39,571
OK DONG-SIK'S FAVORITE BOOK

117
00:04:39,654 --> 00:04:42,073
<i>HOW TO WIN FRIENDS AND INFLUENCE PEOPLE</i>
BY DALE CARNEGIE

118
00:04:42,157 --> 00:04:43,950
THE GLOBAL BIBLE OF INTERPERSONAL SKILLS

119
00:04:44,493 --> 00:04:46,620
- This is a well-known book.
- Yes.

120
00:04:46,995 --> 00:04:48,872
But for the people who don't know,

121
00:04:48,955 --> 00:04:51,541
could you please explain what it's about?

122
00:04:52,584 --> 00:04:54,795
I first read this book

123
00:04:54,878 --> 00:04:58,048
because my girlfriend
recommended it to me.

124
00:04:58,131 --> 00:05:00,759
- Your girlfriend recommended it?
- Yes.

125
00:05:01,593 --> 00:05:03,428
Was it a breakup gift?

126
00:05:03,512 --> 00:05:06,765
Did she want you to get your life together

127
00:05:07,224 --> 00:05:08,725
- and learn interpersonal skills?
- I'm not sure.

128
00:05:10,936 --> 00:05:12,771
She said, "Please read this book."

129
00:05:12,854 --> 00:05:14,940
Did she say, "Read this book. I beg you"?

130
00:05:15,023 --> 00:05:17,526
I think she did say, "I beg you."

131
00:05:19,069 --> 00:05:21,238
So I read it, and it helped me a lot.

132
00:05:21,321 --> 00:05:24,032
While I was running the restaurant,

133
00:05:24,115 --> 00:05:25,575
I had a hard time

134
00:05:25,659 --> 00:05:27,953
with my relationship with the staff.

135
00:05:28,161 --> 00:05:29,913
There's a phrase from this book.

136
00:05:30,080 --> 00:05:33,542
"Before you blame the other person,
admit your fault first."

137
00:05:35,001 --> 00:05:37,754
Because it's my restaurant,

138
00:05:37,838 --> 00:05:39,214
I thought I was always right.

139
00:05:39,297 --> 00:05:41,466
Because I had my principles as a chef,

140
00:05:41,550 --> 00:05:43,718
I was like,
"My way is the way. Do as I say."

141
00:05:43,802 --> 00:05:45,011
In your kitchen?

142
00:05:45,095 --> 00:05:46,847
- Yes, I was like that.
- Right.

143
00:05:46,930 --> 00:05:49,766
But that didn't help
my relationship with the staff.

144
00:05:50,684 --> 00:05:51,560
I used to be like,

145
00:05:51,643 --> 00:05:53,937
"I did no wrong.
You're the one who's wrong."

146
00:05:54,020 --> 00:05:56,898
But after I read this book,
I realized that was on me.

147
00:05:56,982 --> 00:05:59,693
Once I started to admit my faults,
things worked out.

148
00:06:00,110 --> 00:06:03,613
So if you're someone who runs a business

149
00:06:03,697 --> 00:06:04,990
or a restaurant owner,

150
00:06:05,073 --> 00:06:08,159
I'd like to recommend this book.

151
00:06:08,243 --> 00:06:10,829
It's important to have
your way of doing things.

152
00:06:10,912 --> 00:06:12,414
- That's true.
- But you tried

153
00:06:12,497 --> 00:06:14,916
to change the staff
to conform to your way.

154
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:17,586
When you started to
reflect on what you did wrong,

155
00:06:17,669 --> 00:06:20,171
everyone naturally followed
as you changed yourself.

156
00:06:20,255 --> 00:06:22,257
Yes. The workplace atmosphere improved.

157
00:06:22,340 --> 00:06:25,927
The staff used to be passive,
but they became more proactive.

158
00:06:26,595 --> 00:06:28,763
- It's a life guidebook.
- It is.

159
00:06:28,847 --> 00:06:30,599
- Well put, right?
- Very.

160
00:06:31,892 --> 00:06:32,726
You're eloquent.

161
00:06:32,809 --> 00:06:34,895
FUNDAMENTAL TECHNIQUES IN HANDLING PEOPLE:
GIVE HONEST AND SINCERE APPRECIATION

162
00:06:34,978 --> 00:06:36,521
- I was proud of it.
- Were you?

163
00:06:37,063 --> 00:06:38,189
Yes, I did a good job.

164
00:06:39,399 --> 00:06:42,319
Before I set a price for your book,

165
00:06:42,402 --> 00:06:44,821
- I, Hocrates, the man who asks,
- Yes?

166
00:06:44,905 --> 00:06:47,324
- will now start throwing questions
- All right.

167
00:06:47,407 --> 00:06:49,117
to know more about Ok Dong-sik.

168
00:06:49,200 --> 00:06:51,494
- First, the start of Ok Dong-sik
- Okay.

169
00:06:51,870 --> 00:06:53,413
as a chef.

170
00:06:53,955 --> 00:06:55,373
In the book,

171
00:06:55,457 --> 00:06:58,710
there's a quote
from philosopher Elbert Hubbard.

172
00:06:59,336 --> 00:07:02,839
"We become like that
on which our hearts are fixed."

173
00:07:02,923 --> 00:07:04,466
So, since you were young,

174
00:07:05,008 --> 00:07:07,594
were you fixed on becoming a chef?

175
00:07:07,677 --> 00:07:08,553
No, I wasn't.

176
00:07:08,637 --> 00:07:10,180
- You weren't?
- No.

177
00:07:10,263 --> 00:07:12,891
My original dream was to become a pilot.

178
00:07:13,350 --> 00:07:15,685
- I dreamt of flying a plane.
- I see.

179
00:07:16,311 --> 00:07:18,355
I had to go to the Air Force Academy,

180
00:07:18,438 --> 00:07:21,358
so I applied and went
to a specialized high school.

181
00:07:21,441 --> 00:07:24,319
I had an advantage
the moment I entered that school.

182
00:07:24,402 --> 00:07:26,988
But I horribly failed the test.

183
00:07:27,072 --> 00:07:28,365
After graduation,

184
00:07:28,448 --> 00:07:30,784
since we all received
government scholarships,

185
00:07:30,867 --> 00:07:33,662
everyone had to join the military
as a non-commissioned officer.

186
00:07:34,287 --> 00:07:36,581
- I served five years in the military.
- Okay.

187
00:07:36,665 --> 00:07:39,501
I was discharged
as a sergeant first class.

188
00:07:39,918 --> 00:07:41,378
Then, the IMF crisis hit.

189
00:07:41,461 --> 00:07:42,545
It was a difficult time.

190
00:07:42,629 --> 00:07:43,838
- Bad timing.
- Yes.

191
00:07:43,922 --> 00:07:46,341
I couldn't get a job anywhere.

192
00:07:46,424 --> 00:07:48,885
I tried selling necklaces in Jongno

193
00:07:48,969 --> 00:07:52,138
and delivering home appliances
in Yongsan Electronics Market.

194
00:07:52,222 --> 00:07:54,265
- Right.
- I spent that period that way.

195
00:07:54,349 --> 00:07:57,102
And then, I went to a cram school
to retake the CSAT.

196
00:07:57,185 --> 00:07:58,687
So I studied

197
00:07:58,770 --> 00:08:00,647
- and took the test four times.
- I see.

198
00:08:00,730 --> 00:08:02,691
Three of them were to enter med school.

199
00:08:02,774 --> 00:08:03,692
Med school?

200
00:08:03,775 --> 00:08:05,694
Yes, I studied to go to med school.

201
00:08:05,777 --> 00:08:08,488
I was the last generation
to take the old CSAT,

202
00:08:08,738 --> 00:08:09,864
and I just couldn't pass.

203
00:08:09,948 --> 00:08:12,909
So I decided to try something unique

204
00:08:12,993 --> 00:08:15,120
and applied to study nursing, pharmacy,

205
00:08:15,203 --> 00:08:18,415
and also the Department of Culinary Arts
at Kyung Hee University.

206
00:08:18,748 --> 00:08:22,836
I was accepted into
nursing and culinary arts.

207
00:08:22,919 --> 00:08:25,547
I didn't have money
for living expenses or my studies.

208
00:08:25,630 --> 00:08:27,882
I had to go to the one with a scholarship.

209
00:08:27,966 --> 00:08:30,677
I was admitted to Kyung Hee University
with top scores,

210
00:08:30,760 --> 00:08:32,429
so I received a full scholarship.

211
00:08:32,512 --> 00:08:34,139
- For financial reasons?
- Yes.

212
00:08:34,723 --> 00:08:37,726
Back then, I didn't really
have a definite dream.

213
00:08:37,809 --> 00:08:39,310
I had to make ends meet first.

214
00:08:39,978 --> 00:08:42,981
As I was studying,
I learned that I was meant for it.

215
00:08:43,064 --> 00:08:45,233
I worked part-time
at restaurants run by my seniors,

216
00:08:45,442 --> 00:08:48,153
learned some dishes from the elderly
during school breaks,

217
00:08:48,236 --> 00:08:49,738
and volunteered abroad.

218
00:08:50,196 --> 00:08:54,576
As I was doing that,
I realized that this was my path.

219
00:08:54,659 --> 00:08:56,953
- If you look back now, for example,
- Yes?

220
00:08:57,037 --> 00:08:59,247
do you have any memories
of being good at cooking,

221
00:08:59,664 --> 00:09:01,082
such as cooking instant noodles well?

222
00:09:01,166 --> 00:09:02,834
DID YOU HAVE A KNACK FOR COOKING
SINCE YOU WERE LITTLE?

223
00:09:03,168 --> 00:09:04,002
I'm not sure.

224
00:09:04,419 --> 00:09:06,087
I'm really good at
cooking instant noodles.

225
00:09:06,171 --> 00:09:07,297
I'm aware of it.

226
00:09:07,380 --> 00:09:09,215
I've seen you do it many times.

227
00:09:09,299 --> 00:09:11,801
I'm actually not a big fan
of instant noodles.

228
00:09:11,885 --> 00:09:13,553
I eat it two or three times a year.

229
00:09:14,721 --> 00:09:15,638
HOCRATES EATS SIX PACKS AT ONCE
What?

230
00:09:15,722 --> 00:09:18,266
Yes, only when I'm really craving it.

231
00:09:18,349 --> 00:09:19,601
I save it for then.

232
00:09:19,768 --> 00:09:21,770
When do you crave it? Not every day?

233
00:09:21,853 --> 00:09:23,021
If I could,

234
00:09:23,104 --> 00:09:25,106
if it wasn't unhealthy,

235
00:09:25,523 --> 00:09:27,692
I could eat it for every meal forever.

236
00:09:27,776 --> 00:09:30,278
Mixed cold noodles, black bean noodles,

237
00:09:30,361 --> 00:09:31,738
the noodles from Anseong...

238
00:09:31,821 --> 00:09:33,865
The noodles from Anseong are really good.

239
00:09:33,948 --> 00:09:36,159
- Yes, it's like a white canvas.
- Yes.

240
00:09:36,242 --> 00:09:38,244
- Right.
- It goes with any ingredient.

241
00:09:38,620 --> 00:09:40,497
- You're an expert.
- It really does.

242
00:09:40,580 --> 00:09:43,416
It goes well with shepherd's purse.

243
00:09:43,500 --> 00:09:44,959
- When it comes to food,
- Yes?

244
00:09:45,043 --> 00:09:47,378
I consider the texture to be important.

245
00:09:47,462 --> 00:09:48,713
- That's just me.
- I see.

246
00:09:48,797 --> 00:09:51,424
So I don't just eat
packaged instant noodles.

247
00:09:51,508 --> 00:09:54,177
The packaged ones and the ones in cups...

248
00:09:54,260 --> 00:09:55,970
- Yes.
- Cup noodles.

249
00:09:56,054 --> 00:09:58,431
They have different thicknesses.

250
00:09:58,515 --> 00:10:00,308
- Yes, they're produced differently.
- They...

251
00:10:00,391 --> 00:10:01,267
- Right.
- Yes.

252
00:10:01,643 --> 00:10:03,853
- So I boil the packaged ones first,
- Okay.

253
00:10:03,937 --> 00:10:05,522
and when there's a minute left,

254
00:10:05,605 --> 00:10:06,856
I add the cup noodles.

255
00:10:06,940 --> 00:10:08,817
If you mix the two kinds of noodles,

256
00:10:08,983 --> 00:10:11,611
they have different textures,

257
00:10:11,694 --> 00:10:14,823
so it enhances the flavor.

258
00:10:14,906 --> 00:10:16,116
- You're an expert.
- Yes.

259
00:10:16,199 --> 00:10:17,951
THE CORE OF HIS PHILOSOPHY

260
00:10:19,160 --> 00:10:21,746
I think it's because of what I
experienced in my childhood.

261
00:10:21,830 --> 00:10:25,208
My family was financially struggling
when I was a kid.

262
00:10:25,291 --> 00:10:26,918
- Both of my parents worked.
- I see.

263
00:10:27,001 --> 00:10:30,213
My mom worked
at an instant noodle factory in Daegu.

264
00:10:30,713 --> 00:10:33,675
Once every month,
she'd bring two boxes of noodles.

265
00:10:33,758 --> 00:10:36,344
But the funny thing is,
there were only noodles.

266
00:10:36,427 --> 00:10:38,763
- With no seasoning.
- What?

267
00:10:38,847 --> 00:10:41,975
And the noodles were all broken, too.

268
00:10:42,058 --> 00:10:43,643
Oh, the unsellable ones?

269
00:10:43,726 --> 00:10:45,061
- Yes, the unsellable ones.
- I see.

270
00:10:45,145 --> 00:10:46,729
Here's how my mom cooked them.

271
00:10:47,105 --> 00:10:50,441
She boiled them in water
with Dasida stock powder and chili powder.

272
00:10:50,775 --> 00:10:52,110
And I hated that.

273
00:10:52,193 --> 00:10:54,112
- She brought broken noodles.
- Yes.

274
00:10:54,195 --> 00:10:55,488
And no original seasoning.

275
00:10:55,572 --> 00:10:57,448
Just Dasida stock and chili powder.

276
00:10:57,991 --> 00:11:00,118
I really hated that.

277
00:11:00,577 --> 00:11:03,997
Even now,
I rarely use Dasida in my cooking.

278
00:11:04,497 --> 00:11:07,125
I only have good memories
related to instant noodles.

279
00:11:09,627 --> 00:11:12,172
But there's one that my father likes.

280
00:11:12,255 --> 00:11:13,339
- Which one is it?
- It's...

281
00:11:13,423 --> 00:11:16,676
My father would take instant noodles,

282
00:11:16,759 --> 00:11:18,094
- Okay.
- add ripe kimchi,

283
00:11:18,178 --> 00:11:20,972
and also thin wheat noodles.

284
00:11:21,055 --> 00:11:23,725
He'd add more wheat noodles
than the instant noodles

285
00:11:23,808 --> 00:11:25,894
- so it would be like porridge.
- I see.

286
00:11:25,977 --> 00:11:27,896
Kind of like <i>gaengsigi</i> soup,
kimchi soup with mixed ingredients.

287
00:11:27,979 --> 00:11:29,981
- He used to like that.
- I see.

288
00:11:30,064 --> 00:11:31,232
I remember that.

289
00:11:31,316 --> 00:11:32,984
I remember liking that one.

290
00:11:33,067 --> 00:11:35,236
I like to eat it that way, too.

291
00:11:35,320 --> 00:11:37,155
Yes, people from Gyeongsang-do like it.

292
00:11:37,238 --> 00:11:38,781
- Right, it makes it...
- Yes.

293
00:11:38,865 --> 00:11:40,116
The starch makes it thick.

294
00:11:40,200 --> 00:11:42,493
- Exactly, right?
- Yes.

295
00:11:42,911 --> 00:11:44,913
There's something I forgot.

296
00:11:44,996 --> 00:11:47,123
- I didn't bring my <i>dweji-gomtang.</i>
- I see.

297
00:11:47,749 --> 00:11:50,919
There's a style of instant noodles
I want you to try.

298
00:11:51,002 --> 00:11:52,795
- In our <i>dweji-gomtang</i> broth,
- Yes.

299
00:11:52,879 --> 00:11:53,963
INTRIGUED

300
00:11:54,047 --> 00:11:56,132
- add the seasoning to make it salty.
- Okay.

301
00:11:56,216 --> 00:11:58,760
And then, add the noodles. It's delicious.

302
00:11:58,843 --> 00:12:01,804
It's better if you also add
our boiled pork in there.

303
00:12:02,972 --> 00:12:04,974
I'll make it for you sometime.

304
00:12:05,642 --> 00:12:06,976
I'm excited.

305
00:12:07,060 --> 00:12:08,895
- Because the broth is clear.
- Yes.

306
00:12:08,978 --> 00:12:10,647
It has a deep, savory taste

307
00:12:10,813 --> 00:12:12,398
with a rich pork flavor.

308
00:12:12,899 --> 00:12:14,234
Is today just about instant noodles?

309
00:12:16,027 --> 00:12:17,153
Anyway...

310
00:12:18,071 --> 00:12:20,073
Since you didn't like instant noodles,

311
00:12:20,156 --> 00:12:22,158
what's a memorable childhood dish?

312
00:12:23,159 --> 00:12:24,744
A memorable dish

313
00:12:24,827 --> 00:12:26,412
would be seaweed soup for me.

314
00:12:27,413 --> 00:12:28,957
The one my grandmother made.

315
00:12:29,040 --> 00:12:30,875
Because my parents both worked,

316
00:12:30,959 --> 00:12:33,002
my grandmother raised my siblings and me.

317
00:12:33,211 --> 00:12:35,922
- She cooked for us a lot.
- Right.

318
00:12:36,005 --> 00:12:38,424
Her right arm was paralyzed.

319
00:12:38,508 --> 00:12:40,093
She could only use her left arm.

320
00:12:40,176 --> 00:12:42,178
We had a traditional coal stove.

321
00:12:42,262 --> 00:12:44,264
She put a pot on it

322
00:12:44,347 --> 00:12:46,349
and made seaweed soup almost every day.

323
00:12:46,599 --> 00:12:48,142
One day, I saw that.

324
00:12:48,226 --> 00:12:50,728
You know how seaweed
releases a slimy substance?

325
00:12:50,812 --> 00:12:52,397
- Yes.
- I saw that,

326
00:12:52,480 --> 00:12:54,148
and went, "Did you spit in this?"

327
00:12:54,232 --> 00:12:55,358
Oh, no.

328
00:12:55,441 --> 00:12:57,610
I can never forget

329
00:12:57,694 --> 00:12:59,696
that stupid thing I said.

330
00:12:59,821 --> 00:13:02,031
I don't really like seaweed soup.

331
00:13:02,115 --> 00:13:03,741
I rarely eat it nowadays.

332
00:13:03,825 --> 00:13:06,744
But if I ever have to make it,

333
00:13:06,828 --> 00:13:09,330
I take the best ingredients,
the best seaweed,

334
00:13:09,414 --> 00:13:12,250
and I get the best beef and clams

335
00:13:12,667 --> 00:13:14,419
for the broth of the soup.

336
00:13:15,253 --> 00:13:16,921
That's what I serve to people.

337
00:13:17,005 --> 00:13:18,506
I don't cook it for myself.

338
00:13:18,589 --> 00:13:22,844
That's why seaweed soup
is such a memorable dish to me.

339
00:13:22,927 --> 00:13:24,345
It's a bittersweet memory.

340
00:13:24,429 --> 00:13:26,222
I felt bad for what I said
to my grandmother.

341
00:13:26,306 --> 00:13:27,348
- I see.
- I do.

342
00:13:28,725 --> 00:13:30,351
She has passed away,

343
00:13:30,435 --> 00:13:33,396
but I still remember that.

344
00:13:35,606 --> 00:13:37,775
She must come to mind sometimes.

345
00:13:37,859 --> 00:13:39,319
I remember the situation.

346
00:13:39,402 --> 00:13:41,487
My grandmother was standing
in front of the stove

347
00:13:41,571 --> 00:13:44,073
and cooking with just her left hand.

348
00:13:44,157 --> 00:13:45,742
I remember that very clearly.

349
00:13:45,825 --> 00:13:48,077
Was she forgiving or was she mad?

350
00:13:48,161 --> 00:13:50,663
From what I remember,
she had no expression on her face.

351
00:13:54,709 --> 00:13:56,961
- If she got mad and called you rude,
- Right.

352
00:13:57,045 --> 00:13:58,671
- you wouldn't have felt as bad.
- Yes.

353
00:13:58,755 --> 00:14:00,631
I'm sure she was mad.

354
00:14:00,715 --> 00:14:03,676
But she probably thought,
"He's just a kid."

355
00:14:03,760 --> 00:14:05,928
I was her grandson, after all.

356
00:14:06,220 --> 00:14:07,889
That's what I think.

357
00:14:07,972 --> 00:14:09,515
- No, but I think
- Yes?

358
00:14:09,599 --> 00:14:13,019
your grandmother understood
and accepted you.

359
00:14:13,102 --> 00:14:16,898
Yes, since I'm back here,
I should go visit her grave.

360
00:14:17,065 --> 00:14:18,274
This reminded me.

361
00:14:19,067 --> 00:14:20,526
Maybe it's not my place,

362
00:14:20,610 --> 00:14:23,321
but she'd probably
be thinking, "It's okay."

363
00:14:23,988 --> 00:14:25,490
"It's okay, Dong-sik."

364
00:14:29,452 --> 00:14:33,039
TO KNOW ALL IS TO FORGIVE ALL

365
00:14:33,122 --> 00:14:37,168
GOD HIMSELF DOES NOT PROPOSE TO JUDGE MAN
UNTIL THE END OF HIS DAYS

366
00:14:37,251 --> 00:14:39,962
FROM <i>HOW TO WIN FRIENDS</i>
<i>AND INFLUENCE PEOPLE</i>

367
00:14:40,046 --> 00:14:42,340
You said you got a job after graduating.

368
00:14:42,423 --> 00:14:44,217
- Yes.
- Where did you work?

369
00:14:44,759 --> 00:14:45,843
I felt hopeless.

370
00:14:45,927 --> 00:14:48,346
No one would take me
because I was too old.

371
00:14:48,429 --> 00:14:52,016
Because the culinary world
is highly hierarchical,

372
00:14:52,100 --> 00:14:54,310
if the new guy is old in age,

373
00:14:54,394 --> 00:14:56,145
it's hard for them to control.

374
00:14:56,229 --> 00:14:58,356
The hierarchy is necessary, right?

375
00:14:58,439 --> 00:14:59,857
Because in the kitchen,

376
00:14:59,941 --> 00:15:02,318
- there's fire, and there are knives.
- Right.

377
00:15:02,402 --> 00:15:03,861
- It's dangerous.
- It is.

378
00:15:03,945 --> 00:15:06,114
Is that why the hierarchy is necessary?

379
00:15:06,197 --> 00:15:08,908
Because it's an intense environment,

380
00:15:08,991 --> 00:15:11,285
it's necessary for the superior to command

381
00:15:11,369 --> 00:15:13,663
and for the subordinate to accept that.

382
00:15:14,330 --> 00:15:16,749
But if the subordinate
is older than the superior,

383
00:15:16,833 --> 00:15:18,459
that's not easy.

384
00:15:18,543 --> 00:15:20,420
- It might be uncomfortable.
- Yes.

385
00:15:20,503 --> 00:15:22,130
It'd be an uncomfortable situation.

386
00:15:22,630 --> 00:15:24,549
So I was worried,

387
00:15:24,632 --> 00:15:27,301
but my professor helped me

388
00:15:27,385 --> 00:15:30,763
get an internship at
the Korean Air in-flight food department.

389
00:15:31,514 --> 00:15:32,515
A great opportunity.

390
00:15:32,598 --> 00:15:33,933
BACK WHEN HE WAS AN INTERN

391
00:15:34,434 --> 00:15:35,768
Instead of becoming a pilot.

392
00:15:35,852 --> 00:15:37,645
Instead of becoming a pilot, I did that.

393
00:15:38,020 --> 00:15:39,439
In the kitchen.

394
00:15:39,772 --> 00:15:40,898
Of Korean Air.

395
00:15:41,566 --> 00:15:43,693
Then is there a difference

396
00:15:43,776 --> 00:15:46,529
between regular food and in-flight meals?

397
00:15:46,612 --> 00:15:49,532
When you eat food mid-air,
your taste buds are dull.

398
00:15:49,615 --> 00:15:51,826
- Really?
- So when it's prepared before flight,

399
00:15:51,909 --> 00:15:53,327
it's more seasoned.

400
00:15:53,411 --> 00:15:55,997
That way,
when the passengers eat it in the air,

401
00:15:56,080 --> 00:15:58,166
they feel it's just right.

402
00:15:59,000 --> 00:16:01,210
- Yes.
- Maybe that's why...

403
00:16:01,669 --> 00:16:02,712
Maybe it's because it's salty.

404
00:16:02,795 --> 00:16:05,131
I get bloated
after eating the in-flight meals.

405
00:16:05,214 --> 00:16:06,340
Maybe it's that.

406
00:16:06,424 --> 00:16:07,633
Or maybe it's because I eat a lot.

407
00:16:08,926 --> 00:16:10,094
The flight attendants always

408
00:16:10,470 --> 00:16:11,679
give me an extra one.

409
00:16:11,762 --> 00:16:13,973
HIS TASTE BUDS ARE THE SAME
EVEN DURING FLIGHT

410
00:16:14,056 --> 00:16:16,934
Compared to when you eat food down here,

411
00:16:17,018 --> 00:16:19,520
FOCUSED
the lower quality is inevitable.

412
00:16:19,604 --> 00:16:21,022
- Because
- Why is that?

413
00:16:21,105 --> 00:16:23,024
everything is cooked down on the ground,

414
00:16:23,107 --> 00:16:25,193
since they can't cook it in the air.

415
00:16:25,276 --> 00:16:27,278
- Do they prepare it in bulk?
- Yes.

416
00:16:27,361 --> 00:16:29,238
- Right.
- After they finish preparing the food,

417
00:16:29,322 --> 00:16:31,908
they put it in the chilling machine
to cool it.

418
00:16:32,074 --> 00:16:34,619
You have to cool it down
to four degrees Celsius

419
00:16:34,702 --> 00:16:36,162
so that bacteria won't grow.

420
00:16:36,621 --> 00:16:39,415
You cool it down
and heat it back up in the air,

421
00:16:39,499 --> 00:16:41,250
so the quality naturally goes down.

422
00:16:42,001 --> 00:16:44,212
I hope people can understand that.

423
00:16:46,297 --> 00:16:47,673
- I have a question.
- Yes?

424
00:16:48,257 --> 00:16:50,843
Why are instant noodles so good on planes?

425
00:16:51,886 --> 00:16:53,012
It's too good.

426
00:16:53,971 --> 00:16:55,056
STUMPED BY HIS UNIQUE COMPLAINT

427
00:16:55,139 --> 00:16:56,766
It's excessively good.

428
00:16:56,849 --> 00:16:58,726
CURIOUS

429
00:16:58,809 --> 00:17:00,394
HOCRATES WAS KICKED OUT FOR ASKING
TOO MANY QUESTIONS, USUALLY FOOD-RELATED

430
00:17:00,478 --> 00:17:02,647
I don't know. Why would that be?

431
00:17:03,439 --> 00:17:05,358
I think it's due to
the pressure difference.

432
00:17:05,733 --> 00:17:07,485
- It may affect the chewiness.
- Right.

433
00:17:07,568 --> 00:17:10,238
The difference in texture,
as you mentioned.

434
00:17:10,321 --> 00:17:11,864
The tongue tastes differently,

435
00:17:11,948 --> 00:17:13,449
so maybe that's why it's better.

436
00:17:14,158 --> 00:17:16,160
HOCRATES' NOODLE RESEARCH NOTES
Even the cup noodles

437
00:17:16,244 --> 00:17:18,955
- come in a fancy bowl on the plane.
- Right.

438
00:17:19,038 --> 00:17:20,957
Maybe that factors in, too.

439
00:17:21,040 --> 00:17:22,542
HE'S PASSIONATE ABOUT INSTANT NOODLES

440
00:17:22,959 --> 00:17:26,045
Maybe preparing in-flight meals
inspired you to fly overseas.

441
00:17:26,546 --> 00:17:27,964
- You went abroad.
- Yes.

442
00:17:28,047 --> 00:17:30,174
- You went to Côte d'Ivoire.
- Yes.

443
00:17:30,258 --> 00:17:31,842
Why did you decide to go there?

444
00:17:31,926 --> 00:17:34,679
If we skip to the future,
after my three-month internship,

445
00:17:35,096 --> 00:17:36,847
I was interviewed to be employed there.

446
00:17:36,931 --> 00:17:38,683
I made it to the final step

447
00:17:39,559 --> 00:17:40,726
but didn't get the job.

448
00:17:40,810 --> 00:17:42,562
I felt lost for three months.

449
00:17:42,645 --> 00:17:45,106
I didn't know what to do.
No place would have me.

450
00:17:45,189 --> 00:17:49,110
Then, the Ambassador of Korea
to Côte d'Ivoire was looking for a chef.

451
00:17:49,193 --> 00:17:50,820
- So I applied.
- Okay.

452
00:17:50,903 --> 00:17:52,488
That's why I went there.

453
00:17:52,572 --> 00:17:54,949
- That's in Africa, right?
- Yes, Africa.

454
00:17:55,032 --> 00:17:57,994
People know it as the country
Didier Drogba is from.

455
00:17:58,077 --> 00:17:59,870
- The soccer player.
- Right.

456
00:18:00,329 --> 00:18:02,623
- Right! He played for Chelsea.
- Yes.

457
00:18:02,707 --> 00:18:03,583
That's right.

458
00:18:03,666 --> 00:18:05,501
He is practically revered
in Côte d'Ivoire.

459
00:18:05,585 --> 00:18:07,587
How? Could you give an example?

460
00:18:07,670 --> 00:18:10,047
Their president was always late

461
00:18:10,131 --> 00:18:11,299
- to any event.
- I see.

462
00:18:11,382 --> 00:18:13,676
But if he knew Drogba would be there,
he would come early.

463
00:18:14,302 --> 00:18:15,928
- He would be there early?
- Yes.

464
00:18:16,012 --> 00:18:18,347
- The president?
- Yes, he's that special.

465
00:18:18,431 --> 00:18:20,016
- He waited for a soccer player?
- Yes.

466
00:18:20,099 --> 00:18:22,435
He's that revered in that country.

467
00:18:23,686 --> 00:18:26,063
What kind of dishes
did you cook at the embassy?

468
00:18:26,147 --> 00:18:28,816
My job was to cook
at the ambassador's residence.

469
00:18:28,899 --> 00:18:32,153
I cooked all three meals
for the ambassador's family.

470
00:18:32,612 --> 00:18:35,656
I was also in charge of any formal dinners

471
00:18:35,740 --> 00:18:38,409
FORMAL DINNER PREPARED BY CHEF OK
or banquets that were held at the embassy.

472
00:18:38,951 --> 00:18:40,328
What did you learn?

473
00:18:40,411 --> 00:18:42,204
Before, I was part of a big system,

474
00:18:42,288 --> 00:18:44,373
preparing food in bulk with many people.

475
00:18:44,457 --> 00:18:45,791
But there, I was on my own.

476
00:18:46,208 --> 00:18:47,460
I had to lead.

477
00:18:47,543 --> 00:18:48,961
For huge banquets,

478
00:18:49,045 --> 00:18:50,630
we'd make 1,000 rolls of <i>gimbap</i>

479
00:18:50,713 --> 00:18:52,423
and <i>japchae</i> for 1,000 people.

480
00:18:52,506 --> 00:18:54,467
A thousand rolls of <i>gimbap</i> are no joke.

481
00:18:57,595 --> 00:19:00,890
That would really make you
the master of <i>gimbap</i>.

482
00:19:01,307 --> 00:19:04,268
After your experience
at the ambassador's residence,

483
00:19:04,352 --> 00:19:06,062
you came back to Korea.

484
00:19:06,145 --> 00:19:08,648
When I came back,
I didn't have anywhere to work.

485
00:19:08,731 --> 00:19:10,316
Someone from my college

486
00:19:10,399 --> 00:19:11,859
needed someone to work

487
00:19:11,942 --> 00:19:13,486
at their restaurant, so I went.

488
00:19:13,569 --> 00:19:15,946
And I worked there for five years.

489
00:19:16,030 --> 00:19:18,449
I was obsessed with cooking for five years

490
00:19:18,532 --> 00:19:20,451
and didn't take care of myself.

491
00:19:20,534 --> 00:19:22,244
I went to see a physician,

492
00:19:22,328 --> 00:19:25,122
and they told me
I needed to be hospitalized right away.

493
00:19:25,665 --> 00:19:27,500
Was it because of the severe stress?

494
00:19:27,583 --> 00:19:28,793
I was very stressed.

495
00:19:28,876 --> 00:19:30,294
Always worried about sales.

496
00:19:30,378 --> 00:19:32,546
- The responsibility of the head chef.
- Exactly.

497
00:19:32,630 --> 00:19:35,132
Yes, so I was hospitalized
for three weeks.

498
00:19:36,759 --> 00:19:40,179
On the first day,
I was lying in my hospital bed,

499
00:19:40,513 --> 00:19:42,640
and tears just kept falling.

500
00:19:42,723 --> 00:19:44,183
"I've wasted my life."

501
00:19:45,059 --> 00:19:47,478
I thought I was going to die.

502
00:19:48,062 --> 00:19:49,814
The doctor actually said that.

503
00:19:49,897 --> 00:19:52,108
"You would've died if you had come later."

504
00:19:52,775 --> 00:19:55,403
After that, I quit right away.

505
00:19:55,820 --> 00:19:58,030
I went to my parents, who were in Yangsan.

506
00:19:58,114 --> 00:19:59,407
Do you know Naewonsa?

507
00:19:59,490 --> 00:20:01,283
- It's a famous temple.
- Right.

508
00:20:01,367 --> 00:20:04,537
I rested there for a year doing nothing.

509
00:20:05,079 --> 00:20:06,497
Did you shave your head then?

510
00:20:08,124 --> 00:20:09,125
That's when.

511
00:20:09,417 --> 00:20:10,543
DONG-SIK IS CHRISTIAN

512
00:20:10,626 --> 00:20:13,379
- Maybe.
- You achieved enlightenment.

513
00:20:14,463 --> 00:20:15,589
It just happened.

514
00:20:16,215 --> 00:20:19,009
I was at my parents' near the temple,
not the temple.

515
00:20:19,093 --> 00:20:20,511
So you didn't shave then?

516
00:20:20,594 --> 00:20:21,512
No, not then.

517
00:20:21,595 --> 00:20:23,264
I did lose some hair,

518
00:20:23,347 --> 00:20:24,432
but I didn't shave it.

519
00:20:24,515 --> 00:20:26,392
I had a full head of hair back then.

520
00:20:27,852 --> 00:20:30,104
No need to answer that.

521
00:20:31,397 --> 00:20:33,733
And then, you started your own restaurant.

522
00:20:33,816 --> 00:20:36,444
Yes. After resting for a year,

523
00:20:36,527 --> 00:20:38,487
I worked at a new boutique hotel

524
00:20:38,571 --> 00:20:40,281
- as the head chef.
- I see.

525
00:20:40,364 --> 00:20:42,742
I worked there for a year

526
00:20:42,825 --> 00:20:43,993
before I opened my own restaurant.

527
00:20:44,076 --> 00:20:46,704
Looking at your life story,

528
00:20:46,787 --> 00:20:50,916
I don't think people will be wowed

529
00:20:51,000 --> 00:20:52,960
by your perseverance, to be honest.

530
00:20:53,043 --> 00:20:54,086
Maybe five years max.

531
00:20:55,254 --> 00:20:58,924
HOW TO MAKE PEOPLE LIKE YOU:
LAUGH

532
00:20:59,008 --> 00:21:01,635
- That's how I lived life.
- Five years is not short.

533
00:21:01,719 --> 00:21:03,053
- Right, it's not.
- It's not that short.

534
00:21:03,137 --> 00:21:06,557
So what made you open your own restaurant?

535
00:21:07,016 --> 00:21:08,934
The hotel restaurant
served Korean cuisine.

536
00:21:09,226 --> 00:21:12,062
We used a lot of pork.

537
00:21:12,146 --> 00:21:14,523
There would be a lot of scraps
after preparing the meat.

538
00:21:14,607 --> 00:21:16,108
- Yes.
- They can't be used in the dishes.

539
00:21:16,192 --> 00:21:18,944
To avoid making it go to waste,
I used it for a staff meal.

540
00:21:19,028 --> 00:21:21,405
Instead of beef radish soup,

541
00:21:21,489 --> 00:21:22,823
I made pork radish soup.

542
00:21:22,907 --> 00:21:24,241
And it was delicious.

543
00:21:24,867 --> 00:21:25,826
"What's this?"

544
00:21:25,910 --> 00:21:28,120
When you had it,
was that your eureka moment?

545
00:21:28,204 --> 00:21:29,789
I did think, "This is it!"

546
00:21:30,247 --> 00:21:31,791
- On the first bite?
- Yes.

547
00:21:31,874 --> 00:21:33,501
It wasn't like anything before.

548
00:21:34,502 --> 00:21:37,630
It wasn't like a vision from above.

549
00:21:37,713 --> 00:21:39,840
- It wasn't even for the menu.
- No.

550
00:21:39,924 --> 00:21:41,258
- You were caught by surprise.
- Yes.

551
00:21:41,342 --> 00:21:42,843
That's where it started.

552
00:21:42,927 --> 00:21:44,512
How long did you work on it?

553
00:21:44,595 --> 00:21:45,971
- About five months.
- Five.

554
00:21:46,055 --> 00:21:47,723
- I developed it.
- By yourself?

555
00:21:47,807 --> 00:21:50,142
I tried changing this and that

556
00:21:50,226 --> 00:21:53,896
to find the perfect recipe
for my <i>dweji-gomtang.</i>

557
00:21:54,730 --> 00:21:57,733
OKDONGSIK

558
00:22:03,572 --> 00:22:05,366
PORK SHOULDER

559
00:22:09,954 --> 00:22:11,747
<i>TORYEOM</i>

560
00:22:11,831 --> 00:22:13,916
A METHOD OF POURING HOT BROTH

561
00:22:13,999 --> 00:22:18,128
OVER AND OUT OF RICE OR NOODLES
TO WARM IT UP

562
00:22:21,549 --> 00:22:23,926
DICED GREEN ONION, BLACK PEPPER

563
00:22:31,350 --> 00:22:32,184
<i>DWEJI-GOMTANG</i>

564
00:22:35,479 --> 00:22:39,775
It made me decide to quit my job
and open my own restaurant.

565
00:22:40,192 --> 00:22:43,445
Weren't you nervous about that?

566
00:22:43,529 --> 00:22:46,198
About 95% of the people around me
were against it.

567
00:22:46,282 --> 00:22:49,243
Because the pork bone soup with rice
that we're familiar with

568
00:22:49,326 --> 00:22:51,620
is either thick
or has spicy seasoning paste.

569
00:22:51,704 --> 00:22:53,873
- It's heavily seasoned.
- It's complex.

570
00:22:53,956 --> 00:22:55,207
But mine was too mild.

571
00:22:55,291 --> 00:22:56,750
But I was confident.

572
00:22:56,834 --> 00:22:58,836
I knew it'd be a hit.

573
00:22:58,919 --> 00:23:00,045
Now they all say,

574
00:23:00,129 --> 00:23:02,339
"I told you it'd be a hit,"
but it's not true.

575
00:23:02,423 --> 00:23:03,424
Not from what I remember.

576
00:23:04,008 --> 00:23:04,842
That's what they say,

577
00:23:04,925 --> 00:23:05,968
HE STILL HAS A GRUDGE
but it's untrue.

578
00:23:06,051 --> 00:23:07,761
Everyone tried to stop me.

579
00:23:07,845 --> 00:23:09,388
- I think men...
- Yes.

580
00:23:09,471 --> 00:23:11,223
from what I've learned,

581
00:23:11,307 --> 00:23:13,017
and this is just my opinion,

582
00:23:13,100 --> 00:23:15,311
but these four words are important to men.

583
00:23:15,394 --> 00:23:16,478
"I told you so."

584
00:23:16,854 --> 00:23:18,772
WHAT ALL MEN SAY:
I TOLD YOU SO

585
00:23:18,856 --> 00:23:20,107
"I told you so, Dong-sik."

586
00:23:20,190 --> 00:23:21,483
Everyone said that.

587
00:23:21,567 --> 00:23:22,735
After I'd made it.

588
00:23:23,569 --> 00:23:25,487
- So, pork bone soup with rice.
- Yes?

589
00:23:25,571 --> 00:23:27,573
I'm familiar with beef <i>gomtang,</i>
or beef soup.

590
00:23:27,656 --> 00:23:30,492
<i>- Dweji-gomtang</i> sounds new to me.
- Right.

591
00:23:30,576 --> 00:23:33,746
When it comes to pork broth,
I think of pork bone soup with rice.

592
00:23:34,121 --> 00:23:37,374
I think "soup with rice"
would be an umbrella term

593
00:23:37,458 --> 00:23:39,585
- that encompasses "meat soup."
- I see.

594
00:23:39,668 --> 00:23:42,296
My <i>dweji-gomtang </i>has a clear broth.

595
00:23:43,088 --> 00:23:44,673
- It's not opaque white.
- Okay.

596
00:23:44,757 --> 00:23:46,467
Because it's made by boiling only meat,

597
00:23:46,550 --> 00:23:47,676
it turns out clear.

598
00:23:47,760 --> 00:23:49,470
So I named it <i>"dweji-gomtang."</i>

599
00:23:49,553 --> 00:23:50,679
This is <i>gomtang,</i> meat soup.

600
00:23:50,763 --> 00:23:52,556
There's beef <i>gomtang</i> and chicken <i>gomtang.</i>

601
00:23:52,640 --> 00:23:54,767
There should be one for pork too.

602
00:23:55,643 --> 00:23:56,977
That's true.

603
00:23:57,061 --> 00:23:58,103
That's why I made it.

604
00:23:58,187 --> 00:24:00,356
- There's chicken <i>gomtang, </i>chicken soup.
- Right?

605
00:24:00,439 --> 00:24:02,858
So why not pork? That's why I did it.

606
00:24:02,942 --> 00:24:05,444
- I read this somewhere.
- Yes?

607
00:24:05,527 --> 00:24:08,489
"God made water, but man made wine."
Something like that.

608
00:24:08,572 --> 00:24:11,492
- But I came to my own conclusion.
- Okay.

609
00:24:11,575 --> 00:24:12,868
God...

610
00:24:13,243 --> 00:24:14,620
- made water,
- Yes?

611
00:24:15,287 --> 00:24:17,373
but Ok Dong-sik made broth.

612
00:24:18,457 --> 00:24:20,084
- Thank you.
- How's that?

613
00:24:21,502 --> 00:24:25,047
It's an honor hearing this from Hocrates.

614
00:24:25,422 --> 00:24:27,007
Anyone can do it

615
00:24:27,091 --> 00:24:28,926
with a slight shift in perspective.

616
00:24:29,009 --> 00:24:30,844
The layout of your shop is also unique.

617
00:24:30,928 --> 00:24:33,013
- Yes.
- Is there a meaning behind it?

618
00:24:33,097 --> 00:24:34,598
I wanted to start on my own,

619
00:24:34,682 --> 00:24:35,975
but I was short on money.

620
00:24:36,058 --> 00:24:38,310
So the shop couldn't be big

621
00:24:38,394 --> 00:24:39,770
or have many employees.

622
00:24:39,853 --> 00:24:41,647
So I thought about a way

623
00:24:41,730 --> 00:24:43,315
- to run it by myself.
- Yes.

624
00:24:43,399 --> 00:24:44,984
That's how I came up with that layout.

625
00:24:45,067 --> 00:24:48,445
A lot of people ask
if it's styled like a Japanese restaurant,

626
00:24:48,529 --> 00:24:49,571
but it's not like that.

627
00:24:49,655 --> 00:24:51,865
When I went to the marketplace
with my mother as a kid,

628
00:24:51,949 --> 00:24:53,742
old ladies would have stalls

629
00:24:53,826 --> 00:24:55,619
that were shaped like a U or an L.

630
00:24:55,703 --> 00:24:57,830
They'd have bar-like tables

631
00:24:57,913 --> 00:25:00,499
- and they'd have a big pot in the middle,
- Right.

632
00:25:00,582 --> 00:25:02,793
from where they'd serve agar soybean soup

633
00:25:02,876 --> 00:25:04,253
- or soup and rice.
- Or noodles.

634
00:25:04,336 --> 00:25:05,796
Yes. I got it from there.

635
00:25:05,879 --> 00:25:07,673
I was inspired by the market stalls.

636
00:25:07,756 --> 00:25:09,258
That's where I got the idea.

637
00:25:09,341 --> 00:25:11,552
If the person
who prepared the food serves,

638
00:25:11,635 --> 00:25:13,303
I thought customers

639
00:25:13,387 --> 00:25:15,806
would be able to feel
the thought that went into it.

640
00:25:15,889 --> 00:25:19,393
- I see.
- You can't explain food with words.

641
00:25:19,476 --> 00:25:22,604
I really wanted myself as the chef
to serve as well.

642
00:25:22,688 --> 00:25:23,981
Hence the bar table.

643
00:25:24,064 --> 00:25:27,276
At the same time, I'd need fewer staff.

644
00:25:27,359 --> 00:25:30,029
So it becomes more efficient.

645
00:25:30,112 --> 00:25:32,239
They may sound natural now,

646
00:25:32,322 --> 00:25:33,365
but at the time,

647
00:25:33,449 --> 00:25:35,659
- you tried a lot of new concepts.
- Yes.

648
00:25:35,743 --> 00:25:37,327
<i>- Dweji-gomtang.</i>
- Yes.

649
00:25:37,411 --> 00:25:39,288
- The bar table.
- The bar, yes.

650
00:25:39,371 --> 00:25:42,041
- That was new.
- It wasn't popular at the time.

651
00:25:42,124 --> 00:25:43,042
- I see.
- Yes.

652
00:25:43,125 --> 00:25:44,960
Also, you started a business

653
00:25:45,044 --> 00:25:46,628
- with one item on the menu.
- Yes.

654
00:25:46,712 --> 00:25:47,880
You must have been nervous.

655
00:25:47,963 --> 00:25:49,048
It was simple for me.

656
00:25:49,131 --> 00:25:50,549
I was too tired.

657
00:25:50,632 --> 00:25:53,844
I wanted to enjoy my evenings
like everyone else does

658
00:25:53,969 --> 00:25:55,679
and rest on the weekend.

659
00:25:56,430 --> 00:25:57,931
I planned to open five days a week

660
00:25:58,015 --> 00:25:59,767
only for lunch.

661
00:25:59,850 --> 00:26:01,810
- So I started by selling 50 bowls a day.
- I see.

662
00:26:01,894 --> 00:26:03,771
But it was crazy from day one.

663
00:26:03,854 --> 00:26:06,106
People were lined up,

664
00:26:06,440 --> 00:26:08,400
and we were sold out by noon.

665
00:26:08,567 --> 00:26:11,111
We opened at 11 a.m.
and sold 50 bowls quickly.

666
00:26:12,029 --> 00:26:15,532
We did that for a week
before I decided to do 80 bowls.

667
00:26:15,616 --> 00:26:17,534
- That became 100, and then 200.
- I see.

668
00:26:17,618 --> 00:26:18,994
Now, we don't have a limit.

669
00:26:19,078 --> 00:26:20,579
I'm so grateful.

670
00:26:20,662 --> 00:26:24,666
Do you think it being marketed
as only 50 bowls a day was important?

671
00:26:25,084 --> 00:26:28,754
I think it being limited
definitely factored into the popularity.

672
00:26:28,837 --> 00:26:32,549
I think that worked out marketing-wise.

673
00:26:32,633 --> 00:26:35,761
- The wait makes the food taste better.
- Right.

674
00:26:35,886 --> 00:26:37,096
It has an effect.

675
00:26:37,179 --> 00:26:39,598
But the food actually has to be good.

676
00:26:39,681 --> 00:26:41,350
If it's not,
you're bound to be disappointed.

677
00:26:41,433 --> 00:26:42,726
You're even more disappointed.

678
00:26:42,810 --> 00:26:45,896
Fortunately, I was confident
about the taste.

679
00:26:45,979 --> 00:26:48,690
So we could carry on that way.

680
00:26:49,316 --> 00:26:53,112
"Remember that a person's name is
to that person

681
00:26:53,195 --> 00:26:56,698
the sweetest and most important sound
in any language."

682
00:26:56,782 --> 00:26:58,033
- Yes.
- Yes.

683
00:26:58,117 --> 00:27:00,160
I believe this was from the story

684
00:27:00,244 --> 00:27:02,955
- Yes.
- about President Roosevelt.

685
00:27:03,705 --> 00:27:05,582
You were able to expand into New York

686
00:27:05,666 --> 00:27:08,710
thanks to
your interpersonal relationships?

687
00:27:09,461 --> 00:27:12,339
Yes, I opened my restaurant in 2017,

688
00:27:12,422 --> 00:27:14,424
<i>and while running it for a year,</i>

689
00:27:14,508 --> 00:27:16,885
<i>so many foreign customers came.</i>

690
00:27:16,969 --> 00:27:19,054
And they all loved the food.

691
00:27:19,263 --> 00:27:20,556
"Maybe other countries will enjoy it too."

692
00:27:20,639 --> 00:27:23,183
- They made you believe so.
- Yes.

693
00:27:23,267 --> 00:27:25,394
One time, a French customer came in.

694
00:27:25,477 --> 00:27:27,646
He was a middle-aged man.

695
00:27:27,729 --> 00:27:29,106
He spoke a little Korean.

696
00:27:29,189 --> 00:27:31,733
He said, "Man, take this to Paris.
It'll be a hit."

697
00:27:33,569 --> 00:27:34,611
He said, "Man"?

698
00:27:34,695 --> 00:27:36,363
After he was done eating.

699
00:27:36,446 --> 00:27:39,408
After he ate, he was in thought
before he told me.

700
00:27:39,491 --> 00:27:41,535
Wasn't he being too informal?

701
00:27:41,618 --> 00:27:44,830
I was paraphrasing.
That was just the gist.

702
00:27:44,913 --> 00:27:47,457
Things like that kept happening.

703
00:27:47,833 --> 00:27:49,334
Then, in 2018,

704
00:27:49,793 --> 00:27:51,545
I wanted to go on a culinary tour,

705
00:27:51,628 --> 00:27:54,298
so I went to the center of it all,
New York City.

706
00:27:54,673 --> 00:27:58,719
One of my college friends
had already made it in the city.

707
00:27:58,802 --> 00:28:01,013
His restaurant is number one in the US.

708
00:28:01,096 --> 00:28:04,266
- Park Jung-hyun, the owner of Atomix.
- Right.

709
00:28:04,349 --> 00:28:08,812
He wanted to introduce me to someone.

710
00:28:08,896 --> 00:28:11,481
And that someone
is my current business partner.

711
00:28:12,191 --> 00:28:14,902
They asked me, "What's your dream?"

712
00:28:15,068 --> 00:28:18,697
"I want to open an Okdongsik shop
in every gourmet city in the world."

713
00:28:20,574 --> 00:28:22,618
They said, "Let's make it happen."

714
00:28:22,701 --> 00:28:24,828
And that dream came true last year.

715
00:28:26,496 --> 00:28:27,414
Yes.

716
00:28:27,497 --> 00:28:30,000
Paris, Seoul, Tokyo, and New York.

717
00:28:30,709 --> 00:28:32,586
We opened in all of those cities.

718
00:28:33,545 --> 00:28:34,880
If you desperately hope...

719
00:28:34,963 --> 00:28:36,590
Everything comes true, I think.

720
00:28:36,673 --> 00:28:38,926
So, just like that,

721
00:28:39,009 --> 00:28:41,136
<i>we opened a pop-up store in New York.</i>

722
00:28:41,220 --> 00:28:43,222
<i>To open up shop from the start</i>

723
00:28:43,305 --> 00:28:45,474
<i>would've been</i>
<i>too much pressure financially.</i>

724
00:28:45,557 --> 00:28:47,476
<i>- Of course.</i>
<i>- Because it's New York.</i>

725
00:28:47,559 --> 00:28:48,936
From the very first day,

726
00:28:49,019 --> 00:28:51,480
<i>we were fully booked.</i>

727
00:28:51,563 --> 00:28:53,106
On top of that,

728
00:28:53,190 --> 00:28:55,275
there were 980 people
waiting to make a reservation.

729
00:28:56,151 --> 00:28:58,987
I was just doing toryeom, cooking,

730
00:28:59,071 --> 00:29:01,365
<i>making kimchi and dumplings in the kitchen</i>

731
00:29:01,448 --> 00:29:02,491
<i>and coming back up.</i>

732
00:29:02,574 --> 00:29:04,159
<i>That was all I did for four months.</i>

733
00:29:04,785 --> 00:29:07,537
The business side
must be so different from cooking.

734
00:29:07,621 --> 00:29:08,956
Wasn't it a lot of pressure?

735
00:29:09,039 --> 00:29:10,707
<i>I only focused on my food.</i>

736
00:29:10,791 --> 00:29:13,752
<i>The rest was managed by my partner there.</i>

737
00:29:14,169 --> 00:29:15,545
<i>They supported everything.</i>

738
00:29:15,629 --> 00:29:18,590
I think the synergy of both sides

739
00:29:19,091 --> 00:29:20,133
made us successful.

740
00:29:20,217 --> 00:29:21,927
Restaurants don't always become hits

741
00:29:22,010 --> 00:29:23,595
- just because their food is delicious.
- No.

742
00:29:23,679 --> 00:29:25,347
A lot of Koreans came at first.

743
00:29:25,555 --> 00:29:27,849
Korean students studying there

744
00:29:27,933 --> 00:29:30,143
- and a lot of elderly people, too.
- I see.

745
00:29:30,227 --> 00:29:32,896
Because it's like soul food
to Korean people,

746
00:29:32,980 --> 00:29:34,564
they'd come to eat

747
00:29:34,648 --> 00:29:37,025
and bring non-Korean friends
the next time.

748
00:29:37,109 --> 00:29:38,485
That kept happening.

749
00:29:38,568 --> 00:29:40,988
I still remember some of the customers.

750
00:29:41,363 --> 00:29:43,699
It was one day in November...

751
00:29:43,782 --> 00:29:45,367
No, the beginning of December.

752
00:29:45,450 --> 00:29:46,702
It was a very cold day.

753
00:29:47,119 --> 00:29:48,453
An old man came in.

754
00:29:48,870 --> 00:29:51,456
He had a reservation, of course.
He was white.

755
00:29:51,540 --> 00:29:53,625
I asked, and he said he was from Canada.

756
00:29:54,418 --> 00:29:55,794
- He ate and left.
- Okay.

757
00:29:55,877 --> 00:29:57,504
A week later, he came back.

758
00:29:57,587 --> 00:30:00,090
But this time, he brought his grandson.

759
00:30:00,173 --> 00:30:01,341
How'd he hear about it?

760
00:30:01,425 --> 00:30:03,593
I don't know, but he did.

761
00:30:04,011 --> 00:30:06,263
He heard that
a Korean restaurant had opened.

762
00:30:06,346 --> 00:30:07,973
And he really liked the food.

763
00:30:08,056 --> 00:30:09,725
It was easy on his stomach.

764
00:30:09,808 --> 00:30:11,476
So he brought his grandson.

765
00:30:11,560 --> 00:30:13,353
That made me feel very happy.

766
00:30:13,437 --> 00:30:14,688
I still remember

767
00:30:14,771 --> 00:30:16,565
the old man and his grandson.

768
00:30:16,648 --> 00:30:18,692
The customers all became

769
00:30:18,984 --> 00:30:21,361
- promoters of your restaurant.
- That's right.

770
00:30:21,445 --> 00:30:23,280
- Word got around.
- That's right.

771
00:30:23,363 --> 00:30:24,781
Then, you were awarded

772
00:30:24,865 --> 00:30:27,659
<i>the Michelin Bib Gourmand</i>
<i>eight years in a row.</i>

773
00:30:27,743 --> 00:30:28,910
OKDONGSIK SEOGYO BRANCH

774
00:30:28,994 --> 00:30:31,121
BIB GOURMAND

775
00:30:31,204 --> 00:30:34,124
MICHELIN AWARD FOR HIGH-QUALITY,

776
00:30:34,207 --> 00:30:37,461
BUDGET-FRIENDLY RESTAURANTS

777
00:30:37,544 --> 00:30:40,255
It had been three months
since I opened up shop

778
00:30:40,339 --> 00:30:43,300
when I heard
that a Michelin inspector had come.

779
00:30:43,425 --> 00:30:45,260
They said they heard a lot about us.

780
00:30:45,344 --> 00:30:47,721
They liked the food,
so they wanted our info.

781
00:30:47,804 --> 00:30:49,431
- I see.
- So I sent it, and it turns out

782
00:30:49,514 --> 00:30:52,768
that it was for
the Bib Gourmand selection.

783
00:30:52,851 --> 00:30:53,977
I was grateful.

784
00:30:54,061 --> 00:30:56,938
It's not easy to be selected like that
after three months.

785
00:30:57,022 --> 00:30:58,565
- After that,
- Yes.

786
00:30:58,648 --> 00:31:00,859
<i>you made it to the list</i>
<i>of the top eight NYC dishes.</i>

787
00:31:00,942 --> 00:31:01,818
<i>That's right.</i>

788
00:31:01,902 --> 00:31:03,236
This is no ordinary city.

789
00:31:03,320 --> 00:31:05,822
New York has restaurants serving cuisines

790
00:31:05,906 --> 00:31:07,699
- Right.
- from all over the world.

791
00:31:07,783 --> 00:31:09,701
- The center of the world.
- Yes.

792
00:31:09,785 --> 00:31:11,912
I read what Pete Wells wrote.

793
00:31:11,995 --> 00:31:14,456
He's an American flavor columnist,

794
00:31:14,539 --> 00:31:16,458
and he's highly influential.

795
00:31:17,042 --> 00:31:18,710
- This is super important, right?
- Yes.

796
00:31:18,794 --> 00:31:20,712
Everyone gets nervous when he comes.

797
00:31:20,796 --> 00:31:22,506
He said this about your food.

798
00:31:23,048 --> 00:31:24,549
"I can't remember the last time
I tasted a more delicious liquid

799
00:31:24,633 --> 00:31:26,093
that didn't contain
at least some alcohol."

800
00:31:26,176 --> 00:31:27,219
That's right.

801
00:31:27,761 --> 00:31:30,055
- What an expression.
- Right.

802
00:31:38,313 --> 00:31:41,400
- I was unbelievably happy to hear that.
- Right.

803
00:31:41,483 --> 00:31:43,193
- Do you remember this?
- Yes.

804
00:31:43,276 --> 00:31:44,945
- It was in the New York Times.
- Yes.

805
00:31:45,028 --> 00:31:46,279
- It became a hot topic.
- To be honest,

806
00:31:46,363 --> 00:31:48,281
after the pop-up store

807
00:31:48,365 --> 00:31:49,533
was a great success

808
00:31:49,616 --> 00:31:51,535
and things were calming down,

809
00:31:51,618 --> 00:31:53,370
the New York Times article came out.

810
00:31:53,453 --> 00:31:54,788
- Yes.
- Pete Wells

811
00:31:54,871 --> 00:31:57,290
wrote a lengthy critique.

812
00:31:57,541 --> 00:31:59,376
I liked the part you mentioned,

813
00:31:59,459 --> 00:32:01,920
but I also liked
how he said, <i>"siwonhan-mat."</i>

814
00:32:02,087 --> 00:32:04,798
<i>- "Siwonhan-mat."</i>
- Right, in English.

815
00:32:04,881 --> 00:32:07,092
- He just transliterated the phrase.
- Yes.

816
00:32:07,175 --> 00:32:08,468
<i>- "Siwonhan-mat."</i>
- Right.

817
00:32:08,552 --> 00:32:11,638
This is a sensation
that only Korean people know.

818
00:32:11,721 --> 00:32:14,141
I was amazed that he put it that way.

819
00:32:14,224 --> 00:32:17,811
He must have some knowledge
of Korean cuisine.

820
00:32:17,894 --> 00:32:19,771
- That's what I thought.
- I see.

821
00:32:19,855 --> 00:32:21,273
It was published at twelve o'clock.

822
00:32:21,356 --> 00:32:24,276
and people started lining up
at 9 a.m. the next day.

823
00:32:25,402 --> 00:32:26,945
How do you think you were so successful?

824
00:32:27,696 --> 00:32:28,613
How was I successful?

825
00:32:28,697 --> 00:32:31,450
I think I owe it to my sincerity.

826
00:32:31,825 --> 00:32:34,494
My sincerity toward food and customers.

827
00:32:35,203 --> 00:32:37,038
Some people might

828
00:32:37,122 --> 00:32:39,166
- find it strange to hear this,
- Right.

829
00:32:39,249 --> 00:32:40,542
but that's what I think.

830
00:32:40,625 --> 00:32:41,793
In a way,

831
00:32:42,586 --> 00:32:44,087
you didn't compromise.

832
00:32:44,171 --> 00:32:47,632
You didn't compromise
or cater to local demands.

833
00:32:47,716 --> 00:32:50,385
I think that was an important factor
in your success.

834
00:32:50,469 --> 00:32:53,513
I think a paradigm shift
was necessary in Korean cuisine.

835
00:32:53,597 --> 00:32:56,975
In the process of Korean food
establishing itself overseas,

836
00:32:57,058 --> 00:32:59,394
- Yes.
- there have been a lot of modifications.

837
00:32:59,561 --> 00:33:02,105
There have been a lot of changes

838
00:33:02,189 --> 00:33:03,607
to adapt to local tastes.

839
00:33:03,690 --> 00:33:05,400
I don't think that's necessary now.

840
00:33:05,484 --> 00:33:07,319
Because our country's reputation
has grown.

841
00:33:07,861 --> 00:33:10,780
I think it's time to show the world

842
00:33:10,864 --> 00:33:14,326
- some original and authentic Korean food.
- Right.

843
00:33:14,409 --> 00:33:18,455
I thought it was time to show the world
the real taste of Korea.

844
00:33:18,538 --> 00:33:21,249
I can use local ingredients,

845
00:33:21,541 --> 00:33:25,295
but I didn't want the food
to lose the Korean taste.

846
00:33:25,378 --> 00:33:28,924
<i>That's the philosophy</i>
<i>I applied to my food,</i>

847
00:33:29,007 --> 00:33:30,842
<i>and I think that worked.</i>

848
00:33:32,344 --> 00:33:34,387
<i>You didn't want to sully the taste</i>

849
00:33:34,471 --> 00:33:36,598
<i>that dweji-gomtang originally has</i>

850
00:33:36,681 --> 00:33:38,141
- Right.
- to cater to the locals.

851
00:33:38,225 --> 00:33:39,893
- You didn't compromise.
- Right.

852
00:33:39,976 --> 00:33:42,854
South Korea has reached that point.

853
00:33:42,938 --> 00:33:44,564
- That was your judgment.
- Yes.

854
00:33:44,648 --> 00:33:47,192
- I think we're there.
- Our prestige has risen.

855
00:33:48,109 --> 00:33:49,903
When you went to New York,

856
00:33:49,986 --> 00:33:54,533
your friend introduced you
to a great business partner.

857
00:33:54,616 --> 00:33:56,660
At one point,

858
00:33:56,743 --> 00:33:59,412
your professor helped you find a job.

859
00:33:59,496 --> 00:34:02,249
And your girlfriend
introduced this book to you.

860
00:34:02,332 --> 00:34:05,085
A lot of people helped you in life.

861
00:34:05,168 --> 00:34:08,171
- Yes, but besides those cases,
- And...

862
00:34:08,255 --> 00:34:11,383
you, Hocrates, also deeply moved me.

863
00:34:11,466 --> 00:34:12,634
Moved you how?

864
00:34:12,717 --> 00:34:15,011
I had a hard time living in Africa.

865
00:34:15,262 --> 00:34:16,555
But every Sunday,

866
00:34:16,638 --> 00:34:19,933
- KBS World would show <i>2 Days & 1 Night.</i>
- I see.

867
00:34:20,475 --> 00:34:21,935
That comforted me a lot.

868
00:34:22,018 --> 00:34:23,895
- Really?
- Yes.

869
00:34:23,979 --> 00:34:26,481
I waited for that all week.

870
00:34:26,565 --> 00:34:28,942
- That one hour melted away
- Yes.

871
00:34:29,025 --> 00:34:30,193
the stress of the week.

872
00:34:30,944 --> 00:34:35,156
Even now, I watch it on YouTube
when I'm bored in New York.

873
00:34:35,240 --> 00:34:36,908
Not only was it funny,

874
00:34:36,992 --> 00:34:39,995
but it was also a show
that invigorated me.

875
00:34:40,078 --> 00:34:42,539
- I'm not joking. I mean it.
- You're too kind.

876
00:34:42,622 --> 00:34:44,791
It was just as meaningful as this book.

877
00:34:44,874 --> 00:34:46,918
The spring cabbage bibimbap went viral!

878
00:34:47,961 --> 00:34:50,005
Was it the episode set in
the filming location of <i>Mapado?</i>

879
00:34:50,088 --> 00:34:52,007
Yes, that's right. Mapado.

880
00:34:52,090 --> 00:34:53,800
"The cabbage is better than meat."

881
00:34:53,883 --> 00:34:56,261
I still remember that line.

882
00:34:56,344 --> 00:34:57,596
Gosh, I have goosebumps.

883
00:34:57,679 --> 00:35:00,056
- That was the exact line.
- Yes.

884
00:35:00,140 --> 00:35:01,266
- I guess it wasn't a line, but...
- Yes.

885
00:35:01,349 --> 00:35:04,060
I still remember that scene clearly.

886
00:35:04,144 --> 00:35:06,688
That was probably about ten portions.

887
00:35:06,771 --> 00:35:07,731
Wasn't it more?

888
00:35:09,691 --> 00:35:13,320
THE YOUNG MAN TOLD ME
THAT MY SMALL COMPLIMENT AND ENCOURAGEMENT

889
00:35:13,403 --> 00:35:17,115
BECAME A TURNING POINT IN HIS LIFE

890
00:35:17,198 --> 00:35:20,285
FROM <i>HOW TO WIN FRIENDS</i>
<i>AND INFLUENCE PEOPLE</i>

891
00:35:20,744 --> 00:35:23,455
- A lot of people already knew you.
- Yes.

892
00:35:23,538 --> 00:35:26,833
But when you were on <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>,

893
00:35:26,916 --> 00:35:28,376
- more people got to know you.
- Right.

894
00:35:28,460 --> 00:35:30,879
- You chose to have a one-on-one match
- Right.

895
00:35:30,962 --> 00:35:32,130
- with Venerable Sunjae.
- I did.

896
00:35:32,213 --> 00:35:35,300
She's someone I've looked up to
since I was in college.

897
00:35:35,467 --> 00:35:38,553
I was grateful for even getting to cook

898
00:35:38,637 --> 00:35:40,388
in the same space as her.

899
00:35:40,472 --> 00:35:43,642
In the summer
of my sophomore year in college,

900
00:35:43,725 --> 00:35:47,687
she held an event
at a big temple in Suwon.

901
00:35:47,771 --> 00:35:49,856
<i>That's when I first tried</i>
<i>Buddhist temple cuisine,</i>

902
00:35:49,939 --> 00:35:51,232
<i>and I was shocked.</i>

903
00:35:51,941 --> 00:35:54,235
<i>It holds a power</i>
<i>that regular food doesn't.</i>

904
00:35:54,861 --> 00:35:57,989
After that, I got together
with a journalist for <i>Bulkwang,</i>

905
00:35:58,073 --> 00:36:00,241
a Buddhist magazine,

906
00:36:00,325 --> 00:36:03,161
and visited local temples
over a few months,

907
00:36:03,244 --> 00:36:06,081
and experienced food
prepared by Buddhist nuns.

908
00:36:06,164 --> 00:36:09,668
<i>I watched them prepare food, tasted it,</i>
<i>and prepared it with them.</i>

909
00:36:09,751 --> 00:36:12,754
<i>I became fascinated by</i>
<i>Buddhist temple cuisine.</i>

910
00:36:13,296 --> 00:36:14,631
I'm sorry.

911
00:36:15,256 --> 00:36:16,800
- I was already bald by then.
- It's just...

912
00:36:16,883 --> 00:36:18,343
- You're a Christian
- Right.

913
00:36:18,426 --> 00:36:19,761
with Buddhist experience.

914
00:36:21,096 --> 00:36:22,389
You're right.

915
00:36:22,472 --> 00:36:24,140
I was already bald by then.

916
00:36:24,224 --> 00:36:25,642
I decided it was time.

917
00:36:25,725 --> 00:36:27,602
I would blend right in.

918
00:36:27,686 --> 00:36:29,646
That was my thought process.

919
00:36:29,729 --> 00:36:31,064
What is Buddhist temple cuisine like?

920
00:36:31,648 --> 00:36:34,275
When I tasted it, it tasted pure.

921
00:36:34,359 --> 00:36:36,486
I think the most important thing in food

922
00:36:36,569 --> 00:36:37,862
is how it feels after eating.

923
00:36:37,946 --> 00:36:39,447
- Yes.
- It should taste good.

924
00:36:39,531 --> 00:36:41,908
But how it feels after eating it
is really important.

925
00:36:41,991 --> 00:36:44,703
With Buddhist temple cuisine,
I felt so happy after eating.

926
00:36:45,328 --> 00:36:46,413
It's easy on the body,

927
00:36:46,496 --> 00:36:49,916
and the aftertaste lasts very long.

928
00:36:49,999 --> 00:36:52,335
So I'd always been thinking

929
00:36:52,419 --> 00:36:53,962
I wanted to try
making food like this someday.

930
00:36:54,045 --> 00:36:56,214
- And the opportunity came to me that day.
- Right.

931
00:36:56,297 --> 00:36:57,424
It was a challenge for me.

932
00:36:57,507 --> 00:36:59,092
Not the match with Venerable Sunjae,

933
00:36:59,509 --> 00:37:02,512
but preparing the food
was a challenge in itself.

934
00:37:02,595 --> 00:37:04,139
Now that I think of it,

935
00:37:04,222 --> 00:37:06,891
when I think of a good food combination,

936
00:37:06,975 --> 00:37:08,935
I like when I taste it, and it's good,

937
00:37:09,018 --> 00:37:10,729
but if I swallow it,

938
00:37:10,812 --> 00:37:12,772
- and there's a certain aftertaste,
- yes.

939
00:37:12,856 --> 00:37:14,649
- that's what captivates me.
- Right.

940
00:37:14,733 --> 00:37:17,068
Just like Pete Wells said,

941
00:37:17,152 --> 00:37:19,988
it's food with<i> "siwonhan-mat,"</i>
a refreshing taste.

942
00:37:20,447 --> 00:37:22,532
It's not "cool" or "cold."

943
00:37:22,615 --> 00:37:24,075
It's how easy it is on the body.

944
00:37:25,034 --> 00:37:29,205
That's the kind of food
that I aspire to keep making.

945
00:37:29,914 --> 00:37:32,041
Then, is there something

946
00:37:32,125 --> 00:37:36,087
you'd like to prepare the most
as a complete dish?

947
00:37:36,171 --> 00:37:38,214
ONE DISH HE'D LIKE TO PREPARE THE MOST?

948
00:37:40,091 --> 00:37:42,635
When I was in <i>Culinary Class Wars,</i>

949
00:37:42,719 --> 00:37:46,556
and we were asked,
"What dish would you make for yourself?"

950
00:37:46,639 --> 00:37:48,600
I was going to choose seaweed soup

951
00:37:48,683 --> 00:37:50,643
- if I had had the opportunity.
- I see.

952
00:37:51,519 --> 00:37:54,189
I wanted to cook some delicious
seaweed soup with great ingredients

953
00:37:54,272 --> 00:37:56,149
and dedicate it to my grandmother.

954
00:37:56,608 --> 00:37:57,817
That dish.

955
00:37:57,901 --> 00:37:59,736
I, Hocrates, used to say this.

956
00:38:00,445 --> 00:38:02,489
What's the greatest dish in the world?

957
00:38:03,656 --> 00:38:05,909
<i>Dweji-gomtang?</i> Braised short ribs?

958
00:38:05,992 --> 00:38:06,868
<i>Japchae?</i>

959
00:38:08,244 --> 00:38:09,954
But I always say it confidently.

960
00:38:10,663 --> 00:38:11,581
A dish with a story.

961
00:38:11,664 --> 00:38:13,833
THE GREATEST DISH IN THE WORLD
IS ONE WITH A STORY

962
00:38:14,250 --> 00:38:15,960
Your grandmother's seaweed soup

963
00:38:16,044 --> 00:38:18,838
must be the greatest dish to you

964
00:38:18,922 --> 00:38:21,216
- since it's one with a story.
- That's true.

965
00:38:22,300 --> 00:38:23,927
- This is just for me,
- Yes?

966
00:38:24,010 --> 00:38:27,347
but could you imagine
and describe the process?

967
00:38:27,430 --> 00:38:29,265
- If I were to make it now?
- Yes.

968
00:38:29,349 --> 00:38:31,726
- First, I'd go to the market.
- To the market.

969
00:38:31,810 --> 00:38:33,937
And I'd buy the best seaweed from Gijang.

970
00:38:34,020 --> 00:38:35,396
- From Gijang?
- Yes.

971
00:38:35,480 --> 00:38:38,525
Seaweed with the stem on, from Gijang.

972
00:38:38,608 --> 00:38:40,318
Then, I'd soak it briefly.

973
00:38:40,401 --> 00:38:41,945
- Not too long.
- How long?

974
00:38:42,028 --> 00:38:43,071
- About five minutes.
- I see.

975
00:38:43,154 --> 00:38:45,365
Good seaweed doesn't
need to be soaked for long.

976
00:38:45,448 --> 00:38:46,825
- Otherwise, it loses taste.
- I see.

977
00:38:46,908 --> 00:38:49,869
After that, I'd chop it up

978
00:38:50,411 --> 00:38:51,788
- and put it in a pot.
- Okay.

979
00:38:51,871 --> 00:38:53,206
I wouldn't stir-fry it in oil.

980
00:38:53,289 --> 00:38:54,332
What would you do?

981
00:38:54,707 --> 00:38:56,626
According to culinary science,

982
00:38:56,709 --> 00:38:58,503
when you stir-fry it in sesame oil,

983
00:38:58,586 --> 00:39:00,588
it releases harmful substances.

984
00:39:00,672 --> 00:39:02,924
I'd just put it in
and stir-fry it with water.

985
00:39:03,007 --> 00:39:06,344
But I'd stir-fry it
with good Korean beef brisket.

986
00:39:06,427 --> 00:39:07,846
- Stir-fry it.
- Yes.

987
00:39:07,929 --> 00:39:10,390
- A bit of good anchovy sauce.
- No other seasoning?

988
00:39:10,473 --> 00:39:13,101
- Anchovy sauce?
- Yes, just a little bit.

989
00:39:13,184 --> 00:39:15,311
And when the seaweed changes color,

990
00:39:15,395 --> 00:39:17,230
I'd add water to barely cover the seaweed.

991
00:39:17,313 --> 00:39:19,023
- Very little water.
- And I'd boil it like that.

992
00:39:19,107 --> 00:39:21,693
- The seaweed flavor will seep out.
- Right.

993
00:39:21,776 --> 00:39:23,194
Then I'd add more water.

994
00:39:23,278 --> 00:39:25,363
After that, I'd simmer it for a while.

995
00:39:25,655 --> 00:39:27,490
- I'd simmer it--
- On low heat?

996
00:39:27,574 --> 00:39:29,242
Yes, nice and slow.

997
00:39:29,325 --> 00:39:31,244
I wouldn't let it boil. I'd simmer it.

998
00:39:31,327 --> 00:39:32,579
It takes time.

999
00:39:32,662 --> 00:39:34,038
- Low to medium heat.
- Yes.

1000
00:39:34,122 --> 00:39:35,290
After that,

1001
00:39:35,373 --> 00:39:38,334
the broth turns opaque
from the good stuff in the seaweed.

1002
00:39:38,418 --> 00:39:40,920
There's already anchovy sauce

1003
00:39:41,004 --> 00:39:44,382
and the umami from the beef
that are mixing into the broth.

1004
00:39:44,465 --> 00:39:47,010
And I'd add sun-dried sea salt to taste.

1005
00:39:47,093 --> 00:39:48,720
- Only salt?
- Yes, just salt.

1006
00:39:48,803 --> 00:39:49,971
After that,

1007
00:39:50,054 --> 00:39:52,098
I'd taste it and if it needs more salt,

1008
00:39:52,181 --> 00:39:53,933
I'd add clams.

1009
00:39:54,309 --> 00:39:55,727
- To make it salty?
- Yes.

1010
00:39:56,019 --> 00:39:57,937
The clams add saltiness.

1011
00:39:58,021 --> 00:39:59,188
Natural flavor.

1012
00:39:59,272 --> 00:40:01,482
It adds saltiness
and another layer of umami.

1013
00:40:01,566 --> 00:40:03,443
- With slight sweetness.
- Umami from succinic acid.

1014
00:40:03,526 --> 00:40:05,403
I'd add that and briefly boil it.

1015
00:40:05,486 --> 00:40:06,779
Clams get tough if boiled for too long.

1016
00:40:06,863 --> 00:40:07,822
- Is that so?
- Yes.

1017
00:40:07,906 --> 00:40:09,365
I'd lightly boil it and taste.

1018
00:40:09,449 --> 00:40:11,326
If it's still not enough,

1019
00:40:11,409 --> 00:40:12,827
add a bit of soup soy sauce.

1020
00:40:12,911 --> 00:40:13,995
- Soup soy sauce?
- Yes.

1021
00:40:14,078 --> 00:40:15,413
I'd add that to taste.

1022
00:40:15,872 --> 00:40:17,665
Then I'd let it sit for that day.

1023
00:40:18,082 --> 00:40:19,208
I'd eat it the next day.

1024
00:40:20,168 --> 00:40:21,127
Why is that?

1025
00:40:21,961 --> 00:40:23,796
Any Korean soup

1026
00:40:23,880 --> 00:40:26,341
- Any soup?
- tastes better the next day.

1027
00:40:26,424 --> 00:40:27,550
Don't you think so?

1028
00:40:27,634 --> 00:40:29,594
Same with kimchi or soybean paste stew.

1029
00:40:29,677 --> 00:40:31,596
All the stews and soups are like that.

1030
00:40:31,679 --> 00:40:32,805
OK DONG-SIK'S SEAWEED SOUP
1. GET SEAWEED FROM GIJANG

1031
00:40:32,889 --> 00:40:34,265
2. SOAK SEAWEED FOR 5 MINUTES
3. CHOP AND STIR-FRY IT IN WATER

1032
00:40:34,349 --> 00:40:36,225
4. STIR-FRY IT WITH KOREAN BEEF BRISKET
5. ADD A BIT OF WATER AND BRING TO A BOIL

1033
00:40:36,309 --> 00:40:37,644
6. ADD MORE WATER AND LET IT SIMMER
7. SEASON WITH SALT

1034
00:40:37,727 --> 00:40:39,354
8. IF IT NEEDS MORE SEASONING, ADD CLAM
AND BOIL BRIEFLY, NOT TOO MUCH!

1035
00:40:39,437 --> 00:40:40,897
9. IF IT NEEDS MORE, ADD SOUP SOY SAUCE
10. EAT IT THE NEXT DAY

1036
00:40:40,980 --> 00:40:44,150
When the umami of meat
and the umami of seafood meet,

1037
00:40:44,233 --> 00:40:45,944
it tastes the best.

1038
00:40:46,110 --> 00:40:48,196
I want to make seaweed soup like that,

1039
00:40:49,030 --> 00:40:51,783
visit my grandmother's grave,

1040
00:40:51,866 --> 00:40:53,743
- I see.
- and serve her a bowl.

1041
00:40:54,577 --> 00:40:55,912
You'd serve her a bowl.

1042
00:40:55,995 --> 00:40:58,790
"I'm here, Grandmother.
I'm sorry I said that."

1043
00:40:58,873 --> 00:41:00,208
I want to tell her that.

1044
00:41:00,667 --> 00:41:02,168
I'm sure she'd say,

1045
00:41:02,627 --> 00:41:05,296
"Dong-sik, it's delicious."

1046
00:41:08,466 --> 00:41:10,468
HE'S A VERY BUSY MAN

1047
00:41:10,551 --> 00:41:15,306
BUT HE WOULD CALL HIS MOTHER TWICE A DAY
UNTIL THE DAY SHE DIED

1048
00:41:15,390 --> 00:41:18,101
DO YOU THINK
HE HAD AMAZING NEWS EVERY TIME?

1049
00:41:18,184 --> 00:41:20,436
THAT WASN'T THE CASE,

1050
00:41:20,520 --> 00:41:24,565
BUT SHOWING A LITTLE BIT OF ATTENTION
SHOWS YOU'RE THINKING ABOUT THAT PERSON

1051
00:41:24,649 --> 00:41:27,735
FROM <i>HOW TO WIN FRIENDS</i>
<i>AND INFLUENCE PEOPLE</i>

1052
00:41:27,819 --> 00:41:29,988
So how much will you pay for my book?

1053
00:41:30,071 --> 00:41:33,366
- You asked me the price of your book.
- Yes.

1054
00:41:35,368 --> 00:41:36,411
I've set a price.

1055
00:41:37,787 --> 00:41:40,748
Ok Dong-sik's favorite book.

1056
00:41:41,749 --> 00:41:42,667
The price is...

1057
00:41:45,086 --> 00:41:46,004
<i>Walden!</i>

1058
00:41:46,087 --> 00:41:47,213
Oh, my.

1059
00:41:47,797 --> 00:41:49,215
- Here you go.
- Okay.

1060
00:41:49,298 --> 00:41:50,508
<i>- Walden</i>, yes.
- Thank you.

1061
00:41:50,591 --> 00:41:52,552
BY HENRY DAVID THOREAU
Seoul, Tokyo, New York, Paris.

1062
00:41:52,635 --> 00:41:54,429
Ok Dong-sik, you rush around

1063
00:41:54,512 --> 00:41:57,890
- all of these busy and glamorous cities.
- Yes.

1064
00:41:57,974 --> 00:42:01,102
I wanted you to take a quiet rest
from time to time.

1065
00:42:01,185 --> 00:42:03,646
This is a book that's like
a little cabin in the woods.

1066
00:42:03,730 --> 00:42:05,648
I give you <i>Walden</i> as a gift.

1067
00:42:06,107 --> 00:42:06,983
Thank you.

1068
00:42:08,401 --> 00:42:10,403
I have to read it. I love it.

1069
00:42:10,486 --> 00:42:12,530
- Thank you.
- When you're weary,

1070
00:42:12,697 --> 00:42:15,074
I hope you can take a rest
in this cabin-like book.

1071
00:42:15,158 --> 00:42:18,119
I, Hocrates, will be rooting for you.

1072
00:42:18,202 --> 00:42:19,495
- Thank you.
- Today,

1073
00:42:19,579 --> 00:42:22,165
we heard about Ok Dong-sik's tasty life.

1074
00:42:22,248 --> 00:42:24,250
What a great read!

1075
00:42:24,333 --> 00:42:26,377
NEXT CUSTOMER

1076
00:42:26,461 --> 00:42:27,837
- Hello.
- AKMU!

1077
00:42:28,796 --> 00:42:30,548
- You're them, right?
- How did you know?

1078
00:42:30,631 --> 00:42:32,717
"Your brother is so funny.
What's with him?"

1079
00:42:32,800 --> 00:42:33,801
They would say that.

1080
00:42:33,885 --> 00:42:35,178
I'm that influential.

1081
00:42:35,970 --> 00:42:38,389
That's when I started going,
"What's wrong with him?"

1082
00:42:38,473 --> 00:42:40,600
- Did anyone want to meet him?
- No.

1083
00:42:42,018 --> 00:42:43,269
I think we can move on.

1084
00:42:44,437 --> 00:42:45,938
Let's move on, then.

1085
00:42:47,065 --> 00:42:49,776
WHO IS OK DONG-SIK?

1086
00:42:49,859 --> 00:42:54,197
A PERSON WHO USED THE HARDSHIPS
AS INGREDIENTS TO INFUSE IN HIS LIFE,

1087
00:42:54,280 --> 00:42:57,033
JUST LIKE <i>DWEJI-GOMTANG</i>

1088
00:43:20,181 --> 00:43:22,183
Subtitle translation by Cayle Kim
